NIC - Network Interface Card
What is NIC?
It is an interface between the PC and the Network. In older systems it was seperate but now it comes integrated with the motherboard.
They are categorized in the layer 1 or 2 by different experts.
NIC's contain a unique 48 bit identifier called the Media Access Control Address (MAC Address)
MAC Addresses are always represented in Hexadecimal.
First 6 digits are the OUI(Organizationally Unique Identifier) and the last 6 digits are the device ID.

Windows uses " - "  as a delimiter and Linux and Mac use " : " 

Windows : ipconfig/all 
MAC OS : ifconfig
Linux : ip a
displays the MAC Address of the device. It is called "Physical Address" by the ipconfig. "Link/Ether" by the Linux.

NIC's send and recieve the binary data as pulses of electricity, light or radio waves.

All networks transmit data by breaking them into discrete chunks called Frames.
Frames encapsulate information and data for easier transmission.
This is where the MAC is important:
_________________________________________________________________
|  Reciepient's MAC  |  Sender's MAC  |  Type  |  Data  |  FCS  |
_________________________________________________________________
This is a Frame.

FCS: Frame Check Sequence. uses Cyclic Redundancy Check to verify data.

NIC has 2 jobs 1. Transmit data through the cable. 2. Frame encapsulation, Src and Dst MAC Addresses get added to the frame and error checking.

The model to visualize/ conceptualize the many parts of network is OSI - Open Systems Interconnection Model
It is a 7 layer model

How does it help?
1. Mental tool for diagnosis
2. Common language for network issues

7 layers are:
1. Physical : defines methods of moving data between computers. i.e) Hardwares like Cables, Central Box/Hubs are a part of physical layer

2. Data Link : Has 2 sublayers - MAC SubLayer and Logical Link Control SubLayer. NIC sits on the MAC sublayer(In a sense) . The LLC talks to the OS using the device drivers. It offers multiple network protocols and flow control.

When the network becomes large, there comes a need to introduce logical addressing. This enables us to break the large networks into smaller pieces of networks called Subnets.

A Network Protocal is used to create unique identifier for each system and also a set of rules for issue handling.

3. Network : Containers called Packets are created and addressed so they can be transferred between networks. A unique address called the IP Address is given to each each device on the network. IP address is a logical address.

4. Transport
5. Session
6. Presentation
7. Application

